```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n = n / 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

In this solution, we first check if the number `n` is less than 1. If it is, we immediately return `false` because a negative number is not a power of three. Then, we use a while loop to divide `n` by 3 as long as it is divisible by 3. This is because a power of three can be written as `3^x`, and repeatedly dividing by 3 will eventually result in 1 if `n` is a power of three. If the resulting number is 1 after the loop, we return `true` because `n` is a power of three. Otherwise, we return `false`.

Here's a more concise version of the same solution using the modulo operator (`%`) to check for divisibility:

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        return n > 0 && 3 % n == 0;
    }
}
```

This solution works by checking if `n` is greater than 0 and if `3` divided by `n` has a remainder of 0. If both conditions are true, then `n` is a power of three.

